Date: 4 Apr 2001 16:02 GMT 17:02 UK
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: BBC [edited
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/world/europe/newsid_1259000/1259838.stm>

Disease shadow over German
-------------------------------------
Suspected outbreaks of foot-and-mouth disease in Germany have been given
the all-clear as the country manages to stave off the spread of infection
from the Netherlands. German Agriculture Minister Renate Kuenast warned
against hysteria among those convinced the infection will cross the border.
"I don't believe in saying it's getting closer and closer and thereby
contributing to panic," she said.
On Wednesday, initial tests taken at 3 suspected outbreaks in the regions
of Hesse and North Rhine-Westphalia were found to be negative. [Check site
for map.
There have been small-scale precautionary slaughters at the suspected farms
and 3km exclusion zones have been set up around any farm where animals have
shown symptoms of the disease. But the German Farmers' Union and regional
government are calling for preventative vaccinations along the Dutch border
to stave off what they see as the unavoidable spread of the infection. The
Hesse regional government has already prepared for a vaccination programme.
The regional health ministry says it already has 650 000 doses of vaccine
ready and has put in an order for 1.5 million more.
One amateur farmer has apparently already taken matters into his own hands.
Munich city councilor Bernhard Fricke reportedly faces a DM50 000 ($23 000)
for having vaccinated 3 of his sheep on an organic farm in contravention of
EU regulations.
