Date: 6 Apr 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Telegraph [edited
<http://www.telegraph.co.uk:80/et?ac=002559874442765&rtmo=QwkOkaaR&atmo=tttttttd&pg=/et/01/4/6/nfnm306.html>

Dutch to bring in mobile burners
----------------------------------------
A spokesman for the Dutch Ministry of Agriculture announced that 115 000
animals would have to be destroyed. The infected animals are all located in
the center of the Netherlands, around the cities of Apeldoorn, Deventer and
Zwolle. The area has been sealed off from the rest of the country. The
reason for the delay in destroying the animals is that the Dutch
authorities, under pressure from farmers, are not going to burn the animals
in fields, but are organizing mobile incinerators to visit infected farms.
Lawrence Brinkhirst, the Minister for Agriculture, says that farmers will
receive compensation for destroyed animals within a month. Meanwhile,
almost a month after the first case of foot and mouth in France, most
politicians and farmers believe that the country will be spared an epidemic.
[Byline: Joan Clements and Harry de Quetteville
